                 date few studies have empirically demonstrated the processes
                 that generate this pattern, largely because few populations
                 have direct measures of individual dispersal and pedigree
                 information. Intensive, long-term demographic studies and
                 exhaustive genomic surveys in the Florida Scrub-Jay
                 (Aphelocoma coerulescens) provide an excellent opportunity to
                 investigate the influence of dispersal on genetic structure.
                 Here, we used a panel of genome-wide SNPs and extensive
                 pedigree information to explore the role of limited dispersal
                 in shaping patterns of isolation-by-distance in both sexes,
                 and at an exceedingly fine spatial scale (within ~10 km).
